def testGroup(v,r):
	#Input:		A list v=[n,k,d] consisting of a group order n, a dimension k dividing n,
	#		and a positive integer d; and a parameter r indexing a group in the
	#		SmallGroups library, namely G = SmallGroup(n,r)
	#Output:	This function tests a number of necessary conditions for the existence of
	#		a hyperdifference set consisting of d irreducible representations of
	#		dimension k for G. If the conditions are all met, it returns "true". If
	#		any fail, it returns "false".

	#extract the parameters and make the relevant constants
	n=v[0]
	k=v[1]
	d=v[2]

	m=k^2*d #dimension of the resulting ETF, if it exists

	#create the group and check it is nonabelian
	G = gap.new("SmallGroup("+str(n)+","+str(r)+")")
	if G.IsAbelian():
		return false

	#check that the conjugacy classes are small enough
	gg = G.DerivedSubgroup().Order() #order of the commutator subgroup

	classes = G.ConjugacyClasses()
	for C in classes:
		if G.One() in C:
			continue

		c = C.Size()

		if n/c < n/gg + (n-m)/(n-1):
			return false

	#compute the full character table and pass values to SAGE
	irr = G.Irr()
	goodGuys = [ chi for chi in irr if chi.DegreeOfCharacter() == k ]
	vals = [ chi.ValuesOfClassFunction() for chi in goodGuys ]
	sageVals = [ row.sage() for row in vals ]

	#check that there are actually enough irreducibles of dimension k
	if len(goodGuys) < d:
		return false

	#check the triangle inequality for the character sums
	subsetOfD = set([]) #a known subset of D

	for j in range(1,len(sageVals[0])):
		#convert the j-th column to an algebraic number, and take the l1-norm
		colQQbar = [ QQbar(row[j]) for row in sageVals ]
		s = sum(a.abs() for a in colQQbar)

		if s < sqrt(d*(n-m)/(n-1)):
			#the triangle inequality failed
			return false

		if s == sqrt(d*(n-m)/(n-1)):
			#conditions for equality must be satisfied
			#check the number of phases
			phases = []
			for ind in range(len(colQQbar)):
				val = colQQbar[ind] #the current element of the j-th column

				if val == 0:
					continue
				else:
					#rows with nonzero values must lie in D
					subsetOfD = subsetOfD | set([ind])
					if len(subsetOfD) > d:
						#too many rows were forced to lie in D
						return false

					phases.append(val/val.abs())

			phasesSet = set(phases)
			if len(phasesSet) > 1:
				#there are too many phases, so the inequality should have been strict
				return false


	#on the off chance that D was forced by the above code, check that it is a hyperdifference set
	if len(subsetOfD) == d:
		#convert the values of the characters in D to algebraic numbers
		Dvals = [ [ QQbar(a) for a in sageVals[ind] ] for ind in subsetOfD ]
		#make the row sums and take absolute values, ignoring the column for the identity
		s = [ sum(row[j] for row in Dvals).abs() for j in range(1,len(Dvals[0])) ]
		#check there was just one absolute value
		if len(set(s)) > 1:
			return false

	#if the program makes it this far, all the necessary conditions are satisfied
	return true
